# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alpha-enolase
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 1,3-Bisphosphoglycerate is the conjugate base of 1,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] It is phosphorylated at the number 1 and 3 carbons.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The result of this phosphorylation gives 1,3BPG important biological properties such as the ability to donate a phosphate group to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) in order to form the energy storage molecule adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00118 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 1.2.1.12 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00236 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Enzyme 2.7.2.3 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Compound C00197 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 1,3BPG is a macroergic metabolic intermediate in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] It is created by the exergonic oxidation of the aldehyde in glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The result of this oxidation is the conversion of the aldehyde group into a carboxylic acid group which drives the formation of an acyl phosphate bond.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The latter reaction is the only step in the glycolytic pathway in which NAD+ is converted into NADH.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The formation reaction of 1,3BPG requires the presence of an enzyme called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The high-energy acyl phosphate bond of 1,3BPG is important in respiration as it assists in the formation of ATP.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The molecule of ATP created during the following reaction is the first molecule produced during respiration.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The transfer of an inorganic phosphate from the carboxyl group on 1,3BPG to ADP to form ATP is reversible due to a low ΔG.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This is as a result of one acyl phosphate bond being cleaved whilst another is created.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This reaction is not naturally spontaneous and requires the presence of a catalyst.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This role is performed by the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] During the reaction phosphoglycerate kinase undergoes a substrate induced conformational change similar to another metabolic enzyme called hexokinase.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Because two molecules of glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate are formed during glycolysis from one molecule of glucose, 1,3BPG can be said to be responsible for two of the ten molecules of ATP produced during the entire process.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Glycolysis also uses two molecules of ATP in its initial stages as a committed and irreversible step.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] For this reason glycolysis is not reversible and has a net produce of 2 molecules of ATP and two of NADH.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The two molecules of NADH themselves go on to produce approximately 3 molecules of ATP each.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 1,3-BPG has a very similar role in the Calvin cycle to its role in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] For this reason both reactions are said to be analogous.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] However the reaction pathway is effectively reversed.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The only other major difference between the two reactions is that NADPH is used as an electron donor in the calvin cycle whilst NAD+ is used as an electron acceptor in glycolysis.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] In this reaction cycle 1,3BPG originates from 3-phosphoglycerate and is made into glyceraldehyde 3-phosphate by the action of specific enzymes.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Contrary to the similar reactions of the glycolytic pathway, 1,3BPG in the Calvin cycle does not produce ATP but instead uses it.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] For this reason it can be considered to be an irreversible and committed step in the cycle.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] The outcome of this section of the cycle is an inorganic phosphate is removed from 1,3BPG as a hydrogen ion and two electrons are added to the compound+.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] In complete reverse of the glycolytic pathway reaction, the enzyme phosphoglycerate kinase catalyses the reduction of the carboxyl group of 1,3BPG to form an aldehyde instead.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] This reaction also releases an inorganic phosphate molecule which is subsequently used as energy for the donation of electrons from the conversion of NADPH to NADP+.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Overseeing this latter stage of the reaction is the enzyme glyceraldehyde-phosphate dehydrogenase.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] During normal metabolism in human erythrocytes, ≈19% of the 1,3BPG produced does not go any further in the glycolytic pathway.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] It is instead shunted through the Luebering–Rapoport pathway involving the reduction of ATP in the red blood cells.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] During this alternate pathway it is made into a similar molecule called 2,3-bisphosphoglyceric acid (2,3BPG).
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] 2,3BPG is used as a mechanism to oversee the efficient release of oxygen from hemoglobin.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Levels of this 1,3BPG will raise in a patient's blood when oxygen levels are low as this is one of the mechanisms of acclimatization.
[src:alpha-enolase/1-3-bisphosphoglyceric-acid] Low oxygen levels trigger a rise in 1,3BPG levels which in turn raises the level of 2,3BPG which alters the efficiency of oxygen dissociation from hemoglobin.
[src:alpha-enolase/2-phosphoglycerate] 2-phosphoglyceric acid is an intermediate that is part of the glycolysis pathway, and it is converted into phosphoenolpyruvate (PEP) by an enolase.
[src:alpha-enolase/2-phosphoglycerate] There are three types of enolase enzymes that are able to catalyze the conversion of 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP, which are alpha-enolase, beta-enolase, and gamma-enolase.
[src:alpha-enolase/2-phosphoglycerate] Studies have found that Alpha-enolase is the most common enolase, so it is often the specific enolase used to convert 2-phosphoglyceric acid into PEP.
[src:alpha-enolase/2-phosphoglycerate] Alpha-enolase catalyzes this conversion process by acting as a Hydrolase, which means that alpha-enolase removes a water molecule from the 2-phosphoglyceric acid in order to form PEP.
[src:alpha-enolase/2-phosphoglycerate] Enzyme 5.4.2.1 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:alpha-enolase/2-phosphoglycerate] Compound C00631 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:alpha-enolase/2-phosphoglycerate] Enzyme 4.2.1.11 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:alpha-enolase/2-phosphoglycerate] Compound C00074 at KEGG Pathway Database.
[src:alpha-enolase/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the glycolytic pathway, 1,3-bisphosphoglycerate is dephosphorylated to form 3-phosphoglyceric acid in a coupled reaction producing two ATP via substrate-level phosphorylation.
[src:alpha-enolase/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] The single phosphate group left on the 3-PGA molecule then moves from an end carbon to a central carbon, producing 2-phosphoglycerate.
[src:alpha-enolase/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This phosphate group relocation is catalyzed by phosphoglycerate mutase, an enzyme that also catalyzes the reverse reaction.
[src:alpha-enolase/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] In the light-independent reactions (also known as the Calvin-Benson cycle), two 3-phosphoglycerate molecules are synthesized.
[src:alpha-enolase/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] RuBP, a 5-carbon sugar, undergoes carbon fixation, catalyzed by the rubisco enzyme, to become an unstable 6-carbon intermediate.
[src:alpha-enolase/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] This intermediate is then cleaved into two, separate 3-carbon molecules of 3-PGA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] G3P eventually reacts to form the sugars such as glucose or fructose or more complex starches.
[src:alpha-enolase/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] Glycerate 3-phosphate (formed from 3-phosphoglycerate) is also a precursor for serine, which, in turn, can create cysteine and glycine through the homocysteine cycle.
[src:alpha-enolase/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] 3-phosphoglycerate can be separated and measured using paper chromatography as well as with column chromatography and other chromatographic separation methods.
[src:alpha-enolase/3-phosphoglyceric-acid] It can be identified using both gas-chromatography and liquid-chromatography mass spectrometry and has been optimized for evaluation using tandem MS techniques.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The relative positions of structures along strands of nucleic acid, including genes and various protein binding sites, are usually noted as being either *upstream* (towards the 5′-end) or *downstream* (towards the 3′-end).
[src:alpha-enolase/3] Directionality is related to, but different from, sense.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] Transcription of single-stranded RNA from a double-stranded DNA template requires the selection of one strand of the DNA template as the template strand that directly interacts with the nascent RNA due to complementary sequence.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The other strand is not copied directly, but necessarily its sequence will be similar to that of the RNA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] Transcription initiation sites generally occur on both strands of an organism's DNA, and specify the location, direction, and circumstances under which transcription will occur.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] If the transcript encodes one or (rarely) more proteins, translation of each protein by the ribosome will proceed in a 5′-to-3′ direction, and will extend the protein from its N-terminus toward its C-terminus.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] For example, in a typical gene a start codon (5′-ATG-3′) is a DNA sequence within the sense strand.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] Transcription begins at an upstream site (relative to the sense strand), and as it proceeds through the region it copies the 3′-TAC-5′ from the template strand to produce 5′-AUG-3′ within a messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The mRNA is scanned by the ribosome from the 5′ end, where the start codon directs the incorporation of a methionine (bacteria, mitochondria, and plastids use *N*-formylmethionine instead) at the N terminus of the protein.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] By convention, single strands of DNA and RNA sequences are written in a 5′-to-3′ direction except as needed to illustrate the pattern of base pairing.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 5′-end (pronounced "five prime end") designates the end of the DNA or RNA strand that has the fifth carbon in the sugar-ring of the deoxyribose or ribose at its terminus.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] A phosphate group attached to the 5′-end permits ligation of two nucleotides, i.e., the covalent binding of a 5′-phosphate to the 3′-hydroxyl group of another nucleotide, to form a phosphodiester bond.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] Removal of the 5′-phosphate prevents ligation.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] To prevent unwanted nucleic acid ligation (e.g. self-ligation of a plasmid vector in DNA cloning), molecular biologists commonly remove the 5′-phosphate with a phosphatase.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 5′-end of nascent messenger RNA is the site at which post-transcriptional capping occurs, a process which is vital to producing mature messenger RNA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] Capping increases the stability of the messenger RNA while it undergoes translation, providing resistance to the degradative effects of exonucleases.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] It consists of a methylated nucleotide (methylguanosine) attached to the messenger RNA in a rare 5′- to 5′-triphosphate linkage.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 5′-*flanking* region of a gene often denotes a region of DNA which is not transcribed into RNA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 5′-flanking region contains the gene promoter, and may also contain enhancers or other protein binding sites.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 5′-*untranslated* region (5′-UTR) is a region of a gene which is transcribed into mRNA, and is located at the 5′-end of the mRNA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] This region of an mRNA may or may not be translated, but is usually involved in the regulation of translation.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 5′-untranslated region is the portion of the DNA starting from the cap site and extending to the base just before the AUG translation initiation codon of the main coding sequence.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] This region may have sequences, such as the ribosome binding site and Kozak sequence, which determine the translation efficiency of the mRNA, or which may affect the stability of the mRNA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 3′-end (three prime end) of a strand is so named due to it terminating at the hydroxyl group of the third carbon in the sugar-ring, and is known as the *tail end*.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 3′-hydroxyl is necessary in the synthesis of new nucleic acid molecules as it is ligated (joined) to the 5′-phosphate of a separate nucleotide, allowing the formation of strands of linked nucleotides.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] Molecular biologists can use nucleotides that lack a 3′-hydroxyl (dideoxyribonucleotides) to interrupt the replication of DNA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] This technique is known as the dideoxy chain-termination method or the Sanger method, and is used to determine the order of nucleotides in DNA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 3′-end of nascent messenger RNA is the site of post-transcriptional polyadenylation, which attaches a chain of 50 to 250 adenosine residues to produce mature messenger RNA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] This chain helps in determining how long the messenger RNA lasts in the cell, influencing how much protein is produced from it.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 3′-*flanking* region is a region of DNA that is not copied into the mature mRNA, but which is present adjacent to 3′-end of the gene.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] It was originally thought that the 3′-flanking DNA was not transcribed at all, but it was discovered to be transcribed into RNA and quickly removed during processing of the primary transcript to form the mature mRNA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 3′-flanking region often contains sequences that affect the formation of the 3′-end of the message.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] It may also contain enhancers or other sites to which proteins may bind.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 3′-*untranslated* region (3′-UTR) is a region of the DNA which *is* transcribed into mRNA and becomes the 3′-end of the message, but which does not contain protein coding sequence.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] Everything between the stop codon and the polyA tail is considered to be 3′-untranslated.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] The 3′-untranslated region may affect the translation efficiency of the mRNA or the stability of the mRNA.
[src:alpha-enolase/3] It also has sequences which are required for the addition of the poly(A) tail to the message, including the hexanucleotide AAUAAA.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Coenzyme A (CoASH or CoA) consists of a β-mercaptoethylamine group linked to pantothenic acid (vitamin B5) through an amide linkage and 3'-phosphorylated ADP.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] The acetyl group (indicated in blue in the structural diagram on the right) of acetyl-CoA is linked to the sulfhydryl substituent of the β-mercaptoethylamine group.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] This thioester linkage is a "high energy" bond, which is particularly reactive.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Hydrolysis of the thioester bond is exergonic (−31.5 kJ/mol).
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] CoA is acetylated to acetyl-CoA by the breakdown of carbohydrates through glycolysis and by the breakdown of fatty acids through β-oxidation.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA then enters the citric acid cycle, where the acetyl group is oxidized to carbon dioxide and water, and the energy released is captured in the form of 11 ATP and one GTP per acetyl group.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Konrad Bloch and Feodor Lynen were awarded the 1964 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their discoveries linking acetyl-CoA and fatty acid metabolism.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Fritz Lipmann won the Nobel Prize in 1953 for his discovery of the cofactor coenzyme A.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is a metabolic intermediate that is involved in many metabolic pathways in an organism.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] It is produced during the breakdown of glucose, fatty acids, and amino acids, and is used in the synthesis of many other biomolecules, including cholesterol, fatty acids, and ketone bodies.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also a key molecule in the citric acid cycle, which is a series of chemical reactions that occur in the mitochondria of cells and is responsible for generating energy in the form of ATP.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] In addition, acetyl-CoA is a precursor for the biosynthesis of various acetyl-chemicals, acting as an intermediate to transfer an acetyl group during the biosynthesis of those acetyl-chemicals.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Acetyl-CoA is also involved in the regulation of various cellular mechanisms by providing acetyl groups to target amino acid residues for post-translational acetylation reactions of proteins.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] The acetylation of CoA is determined by the carbon sources.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, glycolysis takes place rapidly, thus increasing the amount of citrate produced from the citric acid cycle.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] This citrate is then exported to other organelles outside the mitochondria to be broken into acetyl-CoA and oxaloacetate by the enzyme ATP citrate lyase (ACL).
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] This principal reaction is coupled with the hydrolysis of ATP.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels CoA is acetylated using acetate by acetyl-CoA synthetase (ACS), also coupled with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Ethanol also serves as a carbon source for acetylation of CoA utilizing the enzyme alcohol dehydrogenase.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Degradation of branched-chain ketogenic amino acids such as valine, leucine, and isoleucine occurs.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] These amino acids are converted to α-ketoacids by transamination and eventually to isovaleryl-CoA through oxidative decarboxylation by an α-ketoacid dehydrogenase complex.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Isovaleryl-CoA undergoes dehydrogenation, carboxylation and hydration to form another CoA-derivative intermediate before it is cleaved into acetyl-CoA and acetoacetate.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Additionally, malonyl-CoA decarboxylase (MCD), present in the cytosol, contributes to the extramitochondrial acetyl-CoA pool by converting malonyl-CoA into acetyl-CoA.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] At high glucose levels, acetyl-CoA is produced through glycolysis.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Pyruvate undergoes oxidative decarboxylation in which it loses its carboxyl group (as carbon dioxide) to form acetyl-CoA, giving off 33.5 kJ/mol of energy.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] The oxidative conversion of pyruvate into acetyl-CoA is referred to as the **pyruvate dehydrogenase reaction**.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] It is catalyzed by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Other conversions between pyruvate and acetyl-CoA are possible.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] For example, pyruvate formate lyase disproportionates pyruvate into acetyl-CoA and formic acid.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] At low glucose levels, the production of acetyl-CoA is linked to β-oxidation of fatty acids.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Fatty acids are first converted to acyl-CoA.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Acyl-CoA is then degraded in a four-step cycle of oxidation, hydration, oxidation and thiolysis catalyzed by four respective enzymes, namely acyl-CoA dehydrogenase, enoyl-CoA hydratase, 3-hydroxyacyl-CoA dehydrogenase, and thiolase.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] The cycle produces a new fatty acid chain with two fewer carbons and acetyl-CoA as a byproduct.
[src:alpha-enolase/acetyl-coa] Within mitochondria, MCD similarly facilitates acetyl-CoA production by decarboxylating malonyl-CoA, thereby supporting metabolic flexibility during low-glucose states.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] There are three different genes that encode isoforms of protein kinase B.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] These three genes are referred to as *AKT1*, *AKT2*, and *AKT3* and encode the RAC alpha, beta, and gamma serine/threonine protein kinases respectively.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The terms **PKB** and **Akt** may refer to the products of all three genes collectively, but sometimes are used to refer to PKB alpha and Akt1 alone.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 is involved in cellular survival pathways, by inhibiting apoptotic processes.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 is also able to induce protein synthesis pathways, and is therefore a key signaling protein in the cellular pathways that lead to skeletal muscle hypertrophy and general tissue growth.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] A mouse model with complete deletion of the Akt1 gene manifests growth retardation and increased spontaneous apoptosis in tissues such as testes and thymus.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Since it can block apoptosis and thereby promote cell survival, Akt1 has been implicated as a major factor in many types of cancer.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 is also a positive regulator of cell migration.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 was originally identified as the oncogene in the transforming retrovirus, AKT8.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt2 is an important signaling molecule in the insulin signaling pathway.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] It is required to induce glucose transport.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] In a mouse which is null for Akt1 but normal for Akt2, glucose homeostasis is unperturbed, but the animals are smaller, consistent with a role for Akt1 in growth.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] In contrast, mice which do not have Akt2, but have normal Akt1, have mild growth deficiency and display a diabetic phenotype (insulin resistance), again consistent with the idea that Akt2 is more specific for the insulin receptor signaling pathway.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The role of Akt3 is less clear, though it appears to be predominantly expressed in the brain.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] It has been reported that mice lacking Akt3 have small brains.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt isoforms are overexpressed in a variety of human tumors, and, at the genomic level, are amplified in gastric adenocarcinomas (Akt1), ovarian (Akt2), pancreatic (Akt2) and breast (Akt2) cancers.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The name Akt does not refer to its function.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The "Ak" in Akt refers to the AKR mouse strain that develops spontaneous thymic lymphomas.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The "t" stands for 'thymoma'; the letter was added when a transforming retrovirus was isolated from the Ak mouse strain, which was termed "Akt-8".
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The authors state, "Stock A Strain k AKR mouse originally inbred in the laboratory of Dr.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Rhoads at the Rockefeller Institute." When the oncogene encoded in this virus was discovered, it was termed v-Akt.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Thus, the more recently identified human analogs were named accordingly.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 is involved in the PI3K/AKT/mTOR pathway and other signaling pathways.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The Akt proteins possess a protein domain known as a PH domain, or pleckstrin homology domain, named after pleckstrin, the protein in which it was first discovered.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] This domain binds to phosphoinositides with high affinity.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] In the case of the PH domain of the Akt proteins, it binds either PIP3 (phosphatidylinositol (3,4,5)-trisphosphate, PtdIns(3,4,5)*P*3) or PIP2 (phosphatidylinositol (3,4)-bisphosphate, PtdIns(3,4)*P*2).
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] This is useful for control of cellular signaling because the di-phosphorylated phosphoinositide PIP2 is only phosphorylated by the family of enzymes, PI 3-kinases (phosphoinositide 3-kinase or PI3-K), and only upon receipt of chemical messengers which tell the cell to begin the growth process.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] For example, PI 3-kinases may be activated by a G protein coupled receptor or receptor tyrosine kinase such as the insulin receptor.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Once activated, PI 3-kinase phosphorylates PIP2 to form PIP3.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Phosphorylation by mTORC2 stimulates the subsequent phosphorylation of Akt isoforms by PDPK1.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Activated Akt isoforms can then go on to activate or deactivate their myriad substrates (e.g. mTOR) via their kinase activity.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Besides being a downstream effector of PI 3-kinases, Akt isoforms can also be activated in a PI 3-kinase-independent manner.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] ACK1 or TNK2, a non-receptor tyrosine kinase, phosphorylates Akt at its tyrosine 176 residue, leading to its activation in PI 3-kinase-independent manner.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Studies have suggested that cAMP-elevating agents could also activate Akt through protein kinase A (PKA) in the presence of insulin.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] *O*-GlcNAcylation of Akt is associated with a decrease in T308 phosphorylation.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 is normally phosphorylated at position T450 in the turn motif when Akt1 is translated.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] If Akt1 is not phosphorylated at this position, Akt1 does not fold in the right way.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The T450-non-phosphorylated misfolded Akt1 is ubiquitinated and degraded by the proteasome.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 is also phosphorylated at T308 and S473 during IGF-1 response, and the resulting polyphosphorylated Akt is ubiquitinated partly by E3 ligase NEDD4.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Most of the ubiquitinated-phosphorylated-Akt1 is degraded by the proteasome, while a small amount of phosphorylated-Akt1 translocates to the nucleus in a ubiquitination-dependent way to phosphorylate its substrate.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] A cancer-derived mutant Akt1 (E17K) is more readily ubiquitinated and phosphorylated than the wild type Akt1.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The ubiquitinated-phosphorylated-Akt1 (E17K) translocates more efficiently to the nucleus than the wild type Akt1.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] This mechanism may contribute to E17K-Akt1-induced cancer in humans.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] PI3K-dependent Akt1 activation can be regulated through the tumor suppressor PTEN, which works essentially as the opposite of PI3K mentioned above.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] PTEN acts as a phosphatase to dephosphorylate PIP3 back to PIP2.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] This removes the membrane-localization factor from the Akt signaling pathway.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Without this localization, the rate of Akt1 activation decreases significantly, as do all of the downstream pathways that depend on Akt1 for activation.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] PIP3 can also be de-phosphorylated at the "5" position by the SHIP family of inositol phosphatases, SHIP1 and SHIP2.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] These poly-phosphate inositol phosphatases dephosphorylate PIP3 to form PIP2.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The phosphatases in the PHLPP family, PHLPP1 and PHLPP2 have been shown to directly de-phosphorylate, and therefore inactivate, distinct Akt isoforms.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] PHLPP2 dephosphorylates Akt1 and Akt3, whereas PHLPP1 is specific for Akt2 and Akt3.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The Akt kinases regulate cellular survival and metabolism by binding and regulating many downstream effectors, e.g.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Nuclear Factor-κB, Bcl-2 family proteins, master lysosomal regulator TFEB and murine double minute 2 (MDM2).
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt kinases can promote growth factor-mediated cell survival both directly and indirectly.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] BAD is a pro-apoptotic protein of the Bcl-2 family.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 can phosphorylate BAD on Ser136, which makes BAD dissociate from the Bcl-2/Bcl-X complex and lose the pro-apoptotic function.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 can also activate NF-κB via regulating IκB kinase (IKK), thus result in transcription of pro-survival genes.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The Akt isoforms are known to play a role in the cell cycle.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Under various circumstances, activation of Akt1 was shown to overcome cell cycle arrest in G1 and G2 phases.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Moreover, activated Akt1 may enable proliferation and survival of cells that have sustained a potentially mutagenic impact and, therefore, may contribute to acquisition of mutations in other genes.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt2 is required for the insulin-induced translocation of glucose transporter 4 (GLUT4) to the plasma membrane.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Glycogen synthase kinase 3 (GSK-3) could be inhibited upon phosphorylation by Akt, which results in increase of glycogen synthesis.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] GSK3 is also involved in Wnt signaling cascade, so Akt might be also implicated in the Wnt pathway.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Its role in HCV induced steatosis is unknown.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 regulates TFEB, a master controller of lysosomal biogenesis, by direct phosphorylation at serine 467.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Phosphorylated TFEB is excluded from the nucleus and less active.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Pharmacological inhibition of Akt promotes nuclear translocation of TFEB, lysosomal biogenesis and autophagy.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 has also been implicated in angiogenesis and tumor development.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Although deficiency of Akt1 in mice inhibited physiological angiogenesis, it enhanced pathological angiogenesis and tumor growth associated with matrix abnormalities in skin and blood vessels.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt proteins are associated with tumor cell survival, proliferation, and invasiveness.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The activation of Akt is also one of the most frequent alterations observed in human cancer and tumor cells.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Tumor cells that have constantly active Akt may depend on Akt for survival.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Therefore, understanding the Akt proteins and their pathways is important for the creation of better therapies to treat cancer and tumor cells.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] 49G→A, p.Glu17Lys) in Akt1 is associated with the Proteus Syndrome, which causes overgrowth of skin, connective tissue, brain and other tissues.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt inhibitors may treat cancers such as neuroblastoma.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Some Akt inhibitors have undergone clinical trials.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] In 2010 Perifosine reached phase II. but it failed phase III in 2012.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Miltefosine is approved for leishmaniasis and under investigation for other indications including HIV.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt1 is now thought to be the "key" for cell entry by HSV-1 and HSV-2 (herpes virus: oral and genital, respectively).
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Intracellular calcium release by the cell allows for entry by the herpes virus; the virus activates Akt1, which in turn causes the release of calcium.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Treating the cells with Akt inhibitors before virus exposure leads to a significantly lower rate of infection.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] MK-2206 reported phase 1 results for advanced solid tumors in 2011, and subsequently has undergone numerous phase II studies for a wide variety of cancer types.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] In 2013 AZD5363 reported phase I results regarding solid tumors. with a study of AZD5363 with olaparib reporting in 2016.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Ipatasertib is in phase II trials for breast cancer.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Akt isoform activation is associated with many malignancies; however, a research group from Massachusetts General Hospital and Harvard University unexpectedly observed a converse role for Akt and one of its downstream effector FOXOs in acute myeloid leukemia (AML).
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] They claimed that low levels of Akt activity associated with elevated levels of FOXOs are required to maintain the function and immature state of leukemia-initiating cells (LICs).
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] FOXOs are active, implying reduced Akt activity, in ~40% of AML patient samples regardless of genetic subtype; and either activation of Akt or compound deletion of FoxO1/3/4 reduced leukemic cell growth in a mouse model.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Two studies show that Akt1 is involved in Juvenile Granulosa Cell tumors (JGCT).
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] In-frame duplications in the pleckstrin-homology domain (PHD) of the protein were found in more than 60% of JGCTs occurring in girls under 15 years of age.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The JGCTs without duplications carried point mutations affecting highly conserved residues.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] The mutated proteins carrying the duplications displayed a non-wild-type subcellular distribution, with a marked enrichment at the plasma membrane.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] This led to a striking degree of Akt1 activation demonstrated by a strong phosphorylation level and corroborated by reporter assays.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Analysis by RNA-Seq pinpointed a series of differentially expressed genes, involved in cytokine and hormone signaling and cell division-related processes.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] Further analyses pointed to a possible dedifferentiation process and suggested that most of the transcriptomic dysregulations might be mediated by a limited set of transcription factors perturbed by Akt1 activation.
[src:alpha-enolase/akt] These results incriminate somatic mutations of Akt1 as major probably driver events in the pathogenesis of JGCTs.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] ENO1 is one of three enolase isoforms, the other two being ENO2 (ENO-γ) and ENO3 (ENO-β).
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Each isoform is a protein subunit that can hetero- or homodimerize to form αα, αβ, αγ, ββ, and γγ dimers.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] The *ENO1* gene spans 18 kb and lacks a TATA box while possessing multiple transcription start sites.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] A hypoxia-responsive element can be found in the *ENO1* promoter and allows the enzyme to function in aerobic glycolysis and contribute to the Warburg effect in tumor cells.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] The mRNA transcript of the *ENO1* gene can be alternatively translated into a cytoplasmic protein, with a molecular weight of 48 kDa, or a nuclear protein, with a molecular weight of a 37 kDa.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] The nuclear form was previously identified as Myc-binding protein-1 (MBP1), which downregulates the protein level of the *c-myc* protooncogene.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] A start codon at codon 97 of *ENO1* and a Kozak consensus sequence were found preceding the 3' region of *ENO1* encoding the MBP1 protein.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] In addition, the N-terminal region of the MBP1 protein it critical to DNA binding and, thus, its inhibitory function.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] As an enolase, ENO1 is a glycolytic enzyme the catalyzes the conversion of 2-phosphoglycerate to phosphoenolpyruvate.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] This isozyme is ubiquitously expressed in adult human tissues, including liver, brain, kidney, and spleen.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Within cells, ENO1 predominantly localizes to the cytoplasm, though an alternatively translated form is localized to the nucleus.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Its nuclear form, also known as MBP1, functions solely as a tumor suppressor by binding and inhibiting the *c-myc* protooncogene promoter, and lacks the glycolytic enzyme activity of the cytoplasmic form.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] ENO1 overexpression has been associated with multiple tumors, including glioma, neuroendocrine tumors, neuroblastoma, pancreatic cancer, prostate cancer, cholangiocarcinoma, thyroid carcinoma, lung cancer, hepatocellular carcinoma, and breast cancer.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] In many of these tumors, ENO1 promoted cell proliferation by regulating the PI3K/AKT signaling pathway and induced tumorigenesis by activating plasminogen.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Moreover, ENO1 is expressed on the tumor cell surface during pathological conditions such as inflammation, autoimmunity, and malignancy.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Its role as a plasminogen receptor leads to extracellular matrix degradation and cancer invasion.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Due to its surface expression, targeting surface ENO1 enables selective targeting of tumor cells while leaving the ENO1 inside normal cells functional.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Moreover, in tumors such as non-Hodgkin lymphomas (NHLs) and breast cancer, inhibition of ENO1 expression decreased tolerance to hypoxia while increasing sensitivity to radiation therapy, thus indicating that ENO1 may have aided chemoresistance.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Considering these factors, ENO1 holds great potential to serve as an effective therapeutic target for treating many types of tumors in patients.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] ENO1 is located on the 1p36 tumor suppressor locus near MIR34A which is homozygously deleted in Glioblastoma, Hepatocellular carcinoma and Cholangiocarcinoma.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] The co-deletion of ENO1 is a passenger event with the resultant tumor cells being entirely dependent on ENO2 for the execution of glycolysis.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Tumor cells with such deletions are exceptionally sensitive towards ablation of ENO2.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Inhibition of ENO2 in ENO1-homozygously deleted cancer cells constitutes an example of synthetic lethality treatment for cancer.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] ENO1 has been detected in serum drawn from children diagnosed with juvenile idiopathic arthritis.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Alpha-enolase has been identified as an autoantigen in Hashimoto's encephalopathy.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Single studies have also identified it as an autoantigen associated with severe asthma and a putative target antigen of anti-endothelial cell antibody in Behçet's disease.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Reduced expression of the enzyme has been found in the corneal epithelium of people suffering from keratoconus.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] CagA protein was found to activate ENO1 expression through activating the Src and MEK/ERK pathways as a mechanism for H. pylori-mediated gastric diseases.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Enolase deficiency is a rare inborn error of metabolism disease, leads to hemolytic anemia in affected homozygous carriers of loss of function mutations in ENO1.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] As with other glycolysis enzyme deficiency diseases, the condition is aggravated by redox-cycling agents such as nitrofurantoin.
[src:alpha-enolase/alpha-enolase] Alpha-enolase has been shown to interact with TRAPPC2.
